description.plain:
Ermias Joseph Asghedom (August 15, 1985 – March 31, 2019), better known as Nipsey Hussle, was a Grammy-award winning hip-hop artist and mogul from the Crenshaw district of South Central Los Angeles, California.

With a name inspired by actor Nipsey Russell, Nipsey Hussle released his first project, Slauson Boy Volume 1, in 2005, and he was featured in XXL’s 2010 Freshman Class alongside J. Cole, Big Sean, Freddie Gibbs, Wiz Khalifa, and Jay Rock among others. Nipsey gained national headlines in 2013 as he sold copies of his Crenshaw mixtape for $100 each. One customer was JAY-Z, who purchased 100 copies in support of Nipsey’s hustle. He then charged $1,000 per copy of his Mailbox Money mixtape in 2014 to continue his #Proud2Pay campaign.

After a decade of releasing several mixtapes and singles, Nipsey released his long-awaited debut album Victory Lap in 2018. The album was nominated in the Best Rap Album category at the 2019 Grammy Awards.

On top of being a rapper, Nipsey was also a community activist and entrepreneur in his Crenshaw neighborhood. He helped establish Destination Crenshaw, a 1.3-mile open-air museum highlighting local art, as well as the Vector 90 STEM workspace and his store The Marathon Clothing.

On March 31, 2019, Nipsey was the victim of a shooting outside of his store on the corner of Crenshaw & Slauson in L.A. He passed away at the age of 33.

On April 11, 2019, thousands of mourners attended a nationally televised celebration of life ceremony held for Nipsey at Staples Center in L.A. The following day, the Los Angeles City Council voted unanimously to rename the intersection of Crenshaw & Slauson as “Nipsey Hussle Square” in his honor. In 2020, Nipsey posthumously won Grammy Awards in the Best Rap Performance category for “Racks in the Middle” with Roddy Ricch and Hit-Boy, and in the Best Rap/Sung Performance category for his collaboration with DJ Khaled and John Legend on “Higher.” On what would have been his 37th birthday, Nipsey Hussle was honored with a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame on August 15, 2022.

description.plain:
Nipsey Hussle’s final record before his untimely murder, “Racks In The Middle” is a collaboration with producer Hit-Boy and L.A. rapper Roddy Ricch.

In this song, Nipsey discusses the fruits of his labor, how he enjoys being at the peak of his career and having the best year of his life. He also reflects on how good it felt to see his grandma on a Jet and how he cannot bring his homie Fatts back to life even with all of the success he’s been tasting.

Nipsey dropped his long-awaited, critically acclaimed debut album Victory Lap on February 16th, 2018. The record debuted in the top 5 of the Billboard 200 and netted him his first Grammy nomination for Best Rap Album in 2019.

This is the last single to be released during Nipsey Hussle’s lifetime before his tragic death on March 31st, 2019.

description.plain:
An obvious play on his own name (“Hustle”), Nipsey samples Jay-Z’s “Hard Knock Life (Ghetto Anthem)” to address the misconception of people who grew up in the hood wanting to live the so-called ‘street life.’

Surrounded by drug and gang violence, the Los Angeles-born emcee turns his Crip-affiliated upbringing into a more productive and beneficial story, explicitly one that ends with success:

The hook is basically saying I don’t do this for nothing. They got this narrative, assuming we want to be in the streets going through what we go through and taking risk. That’s just the farthest thing from the truth.

When asked about the difficulty in clearing the Annie sample, Nipsey said the Roc-A-Fella founder already had a standing arrangement:

When Jay got the record cleared originally, [there] was something in his agreement that made it to where, you know, they would continue to clear it for hip-hop artists, for the Annie sample. They cleared it for us. And then we had to clear Jay[-Z’s] version also because we used the version that he used on his album. But they made it happen for us.

He elaborated on Hov trying to clear the original sample:

I read the book [Jay] put out, Decoded, talking about how they didn’t clear it at first and he had to write them directly and tell a story about just why the song means something to him. And after they got his personal letter, they cleared it for him.

body.plain:
An obvious play on his own name (“Hustle”), Nipsey samples Jay-Z’s “Hard Knock Life (Ghetto Anthem)” to address the misconception of people who grew up in the hood wanting to live the so-called ‘street life.’

Surrounded by drug and gang violence, the Los Angeles-born emcee turns his Crip-affiliated upbringing into a more productive and beneficial story, explicitly one that ends with success:

The hook is basically saying I don’t do this for nothing. They got this narrative, assuming we want to be in the streets going through what we go through and taking risk. That’s just the farthest thing from the truth.

When asked about the difficulty in clearing the Annie sample, Nipsey said the Roc-A-Fella founder already had a standing arrangement:

When Jay got the record cleared originally, [there] was something in his agreement that made it to where, you know, they would continue to clear it for hip-hop artists, for the Annie sample. They cleared it for us. And then we had to clear Jay[-Z’s] version also because we used the version that he used on his album. But they made it happen for us.

He elaborated on Hov trying to clear the original sample:

I read the book [Jay] put out, Decoded, talking about how they didn’t clear it at first and he had to write them directly and tell a story about just why the song means something to him. And after they got his personal letter, they cleared it for him.

description.plain:
“Blue Laces 2” is a sequel to Hussle’s “Blue Laces” off of his 2010 mixtape, The Marathon. Produced by Mike & Keys, Mr. Lee, and Larrance Dopson, who sample 1974’s “Give Me Some of That Good Old Love” by Willie Hutch, Nipsey uses the track to reminisce on his past and elaborates on making ends meet.

Hussle explained the inspiration behind the track in a 2018 interview with NPR:

LeBron James, when he won that first championship, they got footage of him on YouTube in the locker room before the game started and he was playing a song in his headphones. When he took his headphones off, I got the song blast through the headphones and it was “Blue Laces” off the original Marathon. I was real flattered. So I’m like, I wanna make a “Blue Laces 2” on Victory Lap.

description.plain:
With a title inspired by a line from Jeezy’s 2005 track “Trap or Die,” “Last Time That I Checc’d” finds L.A.’s Nipsey Hussle collaborating with Compton’s YG for a West Coast banger where they talk about their ascension in life. The music video was released almost a month before Victory Lap and it features classic scenery from the streets of Los Angeles, as well as blue and red color palettes representing Nipsey’s affiliation with the Rollin' 60s Crips and YG’s affiliation with the Tree Top Pirus, respectively.

The song was played in honor of Nipsey Hussle during a Los Angeles Clippers game at Staples Center a few hours after he passed away on March 31, 2019.

songs.title: Young Nigga

description.plain:
“Young Nigga” is a pseudo-autobiographical song where Nipsey speaks on how he has persevered, working on his craft and sticking with people who he grew up with. He also speaks on how far he has come and what he has achieved. The song is completed by nostalgic “Puff Daddy” adlibs, reminiscent of his late ‘90s adlibs on tracks such as “Victory.”



Diddy happened to be in the studio with Nipsey and the adlibs fit so well that they were incorporated into the song despite not being the initial plan. In an interview with NPR, Nipsey detailed the recording session with Puff:


We really had a legendary session; he got to feel my energy, I got to feel his energy as a producer. And he was in the booth screaming. It was a room full of people and I told everybody, “Hey man, when he comes out that booth, everybody clap just to keep the energy going. Not to stroke no ego, but just to keep the energy up, you know what I mean, to say, I appreciate you giving your all to this record.” It was just a fire session.

We got way more than what we needed. Then I just sat there, edited it later and just kept the lines where he was really responding to what I was saying. But yeah, I think Puff added a lot of dynamics to that record.

songs.full_title: Rap Niggas by Nipsey Hussle
songs.title: Rap Niggas

description.plain:
“Rap Niggas” serves as the lead single to Hussle’s debut studio album, Victory Lap. Throughout the song, Hussle asserts that he’s “nothing like” other rappers in the game—Nipsey’s aggressive style pairs well with the menacing production courtesy of DJ Khalil, Larrance Dopson, and Mike & Keys.

This song is also inspired by 1994’s “Natural Born Killaz” with Ice Cube and Dr. Dre—in an interview with NPR, Hussle described “Rap Niggas” as a “West Coast street anthem,” and also talked of Puffy’s influence on the song:

I originally asked [Puff] to get on ‘Rap Niggas.’ He heard the record and he was like, ‘Yeah, ‘Rap Niggas’ is strong Hussle, but listen to this.‘ And he pulled up [1994’s] 'Natural Born Killaz’ with Ice Cube and Dre. And he said, ‘It don’t sound like that though, bro.’ And this was the version [of 'Rap Niggas’] before the one we put out. It had less production.

description.plain:
Nipsey Hussle recruits Sacramento rapper Mozzy and Atlanta rapper Young Thug for “I Do This,” a 4-minutes-long song on which the three artists' address their realness and dedication.

While Young Thug carries most of the song by contributing the chorus, all three rappers rap one verse on which they elaborate on the loyalty they have for their family, friends, and gang, and dedicate their grind and success to their people.

The song was released as a single three months before the release of Slauson Boy 2 and is one of the two Mozzy and Young Thug features on the album.

description.plain:
“Loaded Bases” is a term regarding the sport of baseball. When bases are loaded, the batting team has a player each on first, second, and third bases. It is a critical moment in the game due to the chance of the batting player hitting a home run, which can send not only him, but everyone else that are on base; granting the team 4 points (one point per player that makes it home.) This could cause the batting team to win the game or turn the tides of a losing start.

Nipsey is up at bat with his debut album. The players on bases could be personified by his friends/family, businesses, and his rap career. If he strikes big with this album, it could send all those factors to a metaphorical home base and have him win the game along with those that are on his side.

It is a critical moment in the game due to the chance of the batting player hitting a home run, which can send not only him, but everyone else that are on base; granting the team 4 points (one point per player that makes it home.) This could cause the batting team to win the game or turn the tides of a losing start.

Nipsey is up at bat with his debut album. The players on bases could be personified by his friends/family, businesses, and his rap career. If he strikes big with this album, it could send all those factors to a metaphorical home base and have him win the game along with those that are on his side.
